On Wednesday, it was announced that inflation has risen to nine percent, its highest level in 40 years. However, data from the Institute of Fiscal Studies (IFS) suggests that the poorest families are facing inflation rises of 10.9 percent. Paul Johnson, director of the IFS said that this is because they "spend a large fraction of their budget on energy and food." Mr Johnson added: "Their benefits of course rose by just 3.1 percent". THIS BLOG IS NOW CLOSED. 